The Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) in the early hours of Wednesday announced the presidential candidate of the ruling All Progressives Congress (APC) as the winner of the presidential election. A former Nigerian lawmaker, Senator Shehu Sani, has asked opposition candidates who lost in the February 25, 2023 presidential election to congratulate Bola Tinubu of the ruling All Progressives Congress (APC) or take legal action to challenge his victory.  The Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) in the early hours of Wednesday announced the presidential candidate of the ruling All Progressives Congress (APC) as the winner of the presidential election.  According to the election results declared by the INEC Chairman, Prof. Mahmood Yakubu, Tinubu, a former Lagos State governor, was declared the president-elect after the 70-year-old polled a total of 8,794,726 votes to defeat his closest rivals, Atiku Abubakar of the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP), Peter Obi of the Labour Party (LP) and Rabiu Kwankwaso of the New Nigeria Peoples Party (NNPP).  Reacting to the outcome of Saturdayâ€™s election, the senator who represented Kaduna Central Senatorial District in the 8th Assembly called on leaders and candidates of opposition political parties to address their supporters and calm them down.  Sani advised the opposition candidates and leaders to either congratulate the winner, Tinubu or seek legal redress in court due to the electoral infractions recorded during the election.  He said, "The candidates & leaders of the opposition should address their teaming supporters. They should either congratulate the winner or take the path of seeking legal redress over the electoral infractions.  "Meanwhile a call for unity and peace is of importance 4 our democracy & country." 